{{Infobox artist | name = Jo Hanson | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_name = <!--only use if different from name--> | birth_date = {{Birth date|1918|08|01}} | birth_place = [[Carbondale, Illinois]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2007|03|13|1918|08|01}} | death_place = [[San Francisco, CA|San Francisco]] | resting_place = [[Bolinas, CA]] | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | nationality = | education = | alma_mater = | known_for = [[environmental art]] | notable_works = | style = | movement = | spouse = | awards = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) --> | elected = | patrons = | memorials = | website = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} --> | module = }}
'''Jo Hanson''' (1918–2007) was an environmental artist and activist based in San Francisco.
== Biography == Jo Hanson was born on August 1, 1918 in [[Carbondale, Illinois]].<ref name="Baker">{{cite web | access-date=April 28, 2015 | url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Jo-Hanson-green-activism-inspired-artwork-and-2608790.php | title=Jo Hanson -- green activism inspired artwork and life | publisher=SFGate | date=March 21, 2007 | last=Baker | first=Jo | website=sfgate.com/}}</ref> She moved to California in 1955, first living in Marin County, before settling in San Francisco in the early 1970s where she purchased and restored [[Nightingale House]], located on Buchanan Street to landmark status.<ref name="Steinman">{{cite web | access-date=April 28, 2015 | url=http://weadartists.org/artist/hansonj | title=JO HANSON: Pioneering Environmental Artist Dies in San Francisco | publisher=Women Environmental Artists Directory | last=Steinman | first=Susan Leibovitz | website=weadartists.org}}</ref><ref name=Recology>{{cite web |url=http://recologysf.com/index.php/jo-hanson |title=Jo Hanson |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2015 |website=recologysf.com |publisher=[[Recology]] |access-date=April 18, 2015}}</ref> Hanson obtained a [[Master of Education]] from the [[University of Illinois]] and a [[Master of Fine Arts]] from [[San Francisco State University]].
Hanson died at her home, of cancer, on March 13, 2007.<ref name=Baker/>
== Career == As an extension of her work on the Nightingale House, Hanson set out to address the litter on her street. Her commitment to sweeping the sidewalk outside her home evolved into a public art project and citywide initiative against littering. Hanson's work was known for incorporating the detritus she collected while sweeping. She analyzed and classified what she found as a way of documenting daily life in her district and felt that it reflected a disconnect between the consumption and production of goods and the natural world.<ref name=WAAW>{{cite web |url=https://www.cla.purdue.edu/waaw/cohn/Artists/Hansonbio.html |title=Biography Jo Hanson |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=www.cla.purdue.edu/ |publisher=Women Artists of the American West |access-date=April 28, 2015}}</ref><ref name="Ponte">{{cite journal|last1=Ponte|first1=Alessandra|title=Garbage Art and Garbage Housing|journal=Log|date=2006|volume=8|pages=99–111|jstor=41765594}}</ref>
For six years during the 1980s Hanson was a vocal member of the San Francisco Arts Commission pushing for the inclusion of underrepresented artists of in the city's art collections, specifically women and people of colour. She also played a key role in saving the [[Coit Tower#Murals|murals of Coit Tower]] and the restoration of the murals at Golden Gate Park's [[Golden Gate Park#Beach Chalet|Beach Chalet]].<ref name=Baker/><ref name=Steinman/>
In 1990 Hanson conceived of and initiated the establishment of the Artist in Residence Program at [[Recology]]. The residency assists artists who use discarded materials in their art and raises public awareness about recycling.<ref name=Recology/><ref name=Zanardi/> Its launch coincided with the introduction of curbside recycling in San Francisco due to state legislation passed in 1989. To date more than 100 artists have participated in the program including Estelle Akamine, Jim Growden, Susan Leibovitz Steinman and William Wareham. Recology has also influenced the development of similar programs such in Philadelphia and Portland.<ref name="Spain">{{cite web|last1=Spain|first1=Sharon|title=Nexus for art & environmental activism: Recology S.F. artist residency Program|url=http://weadartists.org/ca-dump-nexus-for-ecoart|website=WEAD|publisher=Women Environmental Artist Director|accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref>
==Awards== In 1997 Hanson was awarded a Lifetime Achievement Award from the Northern California [[Women's Caucus for Art]].<ref name=NCWCA>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncwca.org/lifetime-achievement-awardees-northern-ca.html |title=WCA Lifetime Achievement Awardees from Northern California |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2015 |website=www.ncwca.org |publisher=Northern California Women's Caucus for Art |access-date=April 28, 2015}}</ref>
== Works == One of Hanson's best known works was ''Crab Orchard Cemetery'', a recreation of her ancestral cemetery in Illinois, which opened at the Corcoran Gallery of Art in Washington, D.C. in 1974.<ref name="Zanardi">{{cite web | access-date=April 28, 2015 | url=http://www.contracostatimes.com/theater-and-arts/ci_12762798?nclick_check=1 | title=Peninsula museum revisits 'Crab Orchard Cemetery | publisher=Contra Costa Times | date=April 28, 2015 | last=Zanardi | first=Bonny | website=www.contracostatimes.com/}}</ref>
