{{Other people}} {{Infobox scientist |name = Jacqueline Nancy Mary Adam |birth_name = Jacqueline Nancy Mary Whittaker |image =
|image_size = |caption = |nationality = [[New Zealand]] |birth_date = {{Birth date|1926|05|19}} |birth_place = [[Levin, New Zealand|Levin]] |death_date = {{Death date and age|2007|03|27|1926|05|19|mf=yes}} |death_place = |resting_place = |residence = |citizenship = |ethnicity = |field = [[Botany]] |work_institutions = |alma_mater = Victoria University of Wellington |doctoral_advisor = |doctoral_students = |known_for = |author_abbrev_bot = |author_abbrev_zoo = |influences = |influenced = |prizes = |spouse = |footnotes = }} '''Jacqueline Nancy Mary Adams''', {{post-nominals|country=NZL|CBE|QSO}} (19 May 1926 – 27 March 2007) was a [[New Zealand]] [[botanist]], [[botanical illustrator|botanical artist]], and [[museum curator]]. Born in Levin in 1926, Nancy Adams attended [[Wellington Girls' College|Wellington Girls’ College]] and [[Victoria University of Wellington]], studying [[zoology]] and botany. At 16 she joined the Botany Division of New Zealand's [[Department of Scientific and Industrial Research (New Zealand)|Department of Scientific and Industrial Research]] (DSIR). She worked there until 1959, when she was appointed to the Dominion Museum (now the [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]]) as assistant Curator of Botany with a special responsibility for algae. She retired from her position at the museum in 1987 but continued to be an Honorary Research Associate of the Museum.<ref name="rnzih">{{cite web|last=New Zealand Garden Journal|title=Obituary|url=http://www.rnzih.org.nz/RNZIH_Journal/Pages_25-26_from_2007_Vol10_No1.pdf|year=2007}}</ref>
Nancy Adams was a prolific artist, illustrating nearly forty publications on native plants, alpine life, trees and shrubs. Included in these publications is an article written by [[Ella Orr Campbell]] a fellow New Zealand botanist, for whom Adams drew ''Thallus of Marchasta bearing archegoniophres''.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Campbell|first1=Ella O.|title=The Liverwort Genus Marchasta|journal=Tuatara|date=November 1961|volume=9|issue=2|page=77|url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/Bio09Tuat02-fig-Bio09Tuat02_078a.html|accessdate=15 March 2015}}</ref> She received international recognition for her detailed and delicate algal illustrations.<ref name="rnzih" /> Awards included the [[Loder Cup]] in 1964, the [[Queen's Service Order]] in 1989, and the [[New Zealand 1990 Commemoration Medal]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Haines|first=Catharine|title=International women in science: a biographical dictionary to 1950|year=2001|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, California|isbn=1-57607-090-5|pages=2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HftdjMNDvwIC&lpg=PA2&ots=cfXuNgS2d-&dq=madge%20adam%20oxford&pg=PA2#v=onepage&q=madge%20adam%20oxford&f=false}}</ref> In 1994 she also received an award for her work ''Seaweeds of New Zealand: An Illustrated Guide'', which held a description of 600 different plant species and illustrating 441.<ref>{{cite web|last=Herald|first=The New Zealand|title=Obituary: Nancy Adams|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10431737|accessdate=4 March 2014}}</ref>
