The '''rash promise''' is a common [[Motif (narrative)|motif]] in [[Medieval literature|medieval]] and [[Oral literature|folk literature]], especially [[fairy tale]]s.<ref name="Mitchell1987">{{cite book|last=Mitchell|first=Jerome|title=Scott, Chaucer, and Medieval Romance: A Study in Sir Walter Scott's Indebtedness to the Literature of the Middle Ages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dPPqR2BMe54C&pg=PA175|accessdate=9 January 2013|year=1987|publisher=UP of Kentucky|isbn=9780813116099|page=175}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Merriam-Webster's Encyclopedia of Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eKNK1YwHcQ4C&pg=PA433|accessdate=9 January 2013|year=1995|publisher=Merriam-Webster|isbn=9780877790426|page=433|chapter=Franklin's Tale, The}}</ref> It was also termed a '''blind promise''' or '''rash boon.''' It is classified as [[Aarne–Thompson classification system|Aarne-Thompson]] M223<ref>{{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Stith|authorlink=Stith Thompson|title=Motif-index of folk-literature : a classification of narrative elements in folktales, ballads, myths, fables, mediaeval romances, exempla, fabliaux, jest-books, and local legends|url=https://www.ualberta.ca/~urban/Projects/English/Content/m.htm|date=1955–58|publisher=Indiana UP|location=Bloomington}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Chaucer|first1=Geoffrey|last2=Benson|first2=Larry Dean|title=The riverside Chaucer: based on The works of Geoffrey Chaucer|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E4DXD7Sk7WcC&pg=PA895|accessdate=9 January 2013|year=2008|publisher=Oxford UP|isbn=9780199552092|pages=895–}}</ref> and likely has an Oriental origin.<ref name=edwards>{{cite book|last=Edwards|first=Robert R.|editor=Robert M. Correale|others=Mary Hamel|title=Sources and Analogues of the Canterbury Tales|volume=1|year=2003|publisher=D. S. Brewer|location=Cambridge|isbn=9780859918282|pages=211–65|chapter=The Franklin's Tale}}</ref>
== Examples == The motif involves a character who makes a promise pertaining to love for another character. The first character promises to grant the other his/her love if an impossible wish is granted. Alternately, the first character could promise the second anything he/she asks for in exchange for escape from a life-or-death situation.
A notable example of the first scenario is [[Geoffrey Chaucer]]'s "[[The Franklin's Tale]]", itself partly based on [[Boccaccio]]'s ''[[The Filocolo]]''; Dorigen, a married woman whose husband is absent, promises another suitor that he may have her if she makes the rocks on the coast of Brittany disappear.<ref name="edwards" /><ref>{{cite book|last=Clouston|first=W. A.|editor=F.J. Furnivall|others=E. Brock, W.A. Clouston|title=Originals and analogues of some of Chaucer's Canterbury tales|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l9gUAAAAQAAJ|year=1872|publisher=Furnivall|pages=289–340|chapter=The Damsel's Rash Promise: Indian Original and Some Asiatic and European Variants of Chaucer's Franklin's Tale}}</ref>
An example of the second variation is found in Chaucer's "[[The Wife of Bath's Tale]]", where the main character, a young rapist knight threatened with execution if he cannot answer the question "What do women want?," promises an older woman (the proverbial "[[loathly lady]]") anything she desires if she can provide the answer (she desires to marry him).<ref>{{cite book|last=Mann|first=Jill|title=Geoffrey Chaucer|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zlX9B4etMxAC&pg=PR10|accessdate=9 January 2013|year=2002|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|isbn=9780859916134|page=10}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Wollock|first=Jennifer G.|title=Rethinking Chivalry and Courtly Love|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=orTn7RpmyZIC&pg=PA169|accessdate=9 January 2013|year=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9780275984885|page=169}}</ref>
